[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Examining checkstyle rules**\n\nI’m exploring checkstyle rules and considering whether I should test without them. There are existing private static final classes, and our nested classes are public so they can be accessed via `getConstructors()`. But can a public constructor exist in a non-public class? When I look at the documentation, it seems that `getConstructors()` returns public constructors of classes regardless of the class's visibility. However, invoking it can fail due to access issues if the declaring class isn’t public.\n\n**Reviewing nested class accessibility**\n\nIf the nested class is private, then the public constructor becomes inaccessible. To prevent this, I think helper nested classes should ideally be public static. But wait, could checkstyle potentially prohibit public nested classes? I don't think so. Fields can be private final without needing getters. However, could checkstyle flag it as a hidden field? Also, I'd like to analyze if constructor parameters sharing names with field names could lead to violations. The existing style might indeed have a hidden field issue, but I’m unsure.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_01be2b24676df61f0169f8d8ba582c81a1a5501e1aea5e9b9c\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-NjDdC-y_i5MHRtNv0z0kOuzeDri67StaKjH6NK38u9ELOWYfIT4-LscCsPLx-k1g2XB946cKbAsz68YWzSdmB26gvx0RljQ8_V2zfl0q5-mXfNVojyajnO1WpnQ_4cL-Xka5-ANR1BZY0nYCO0cbfec5l33mkz8tkCvmBR3cDjNCCGMX9FRReH16oFSCrg-FdBsjhU3G5vjN5674xQi63OeeTHdfTf6VvWdhUMc2jrFa7eA3Q2qQtXc3fZjEgncGaoqqijLDnjmuz3eh7nk1sTjYrRLXZLAyDwskoqow__eLOjzv-i6d_aHbMSyIzzYsyYhdStiA4Z4A1CUQBmY4zW7pEPTK4lashvxKKxffmjOXDUni_Kscz0MYtcx14v-Tqqsn1FTFO7nd2CQyq06YgeAklwiEF49euowliKKIITS83h411ut1qUfnm0AD4EEI4EFR7vN0CU24Dg4udznfPwX1pmFlLhsmfN1slaarO-w2PHfhc3v4OYGjGl4gV7z5vEvfZ-06XNdPyJGKcd9C7-6YKyzn29keNdvllK0h4vfx_-2-K-_HbJZ0AJFUMPLnimREleG7kOL6AQeBMyqS4f3nkle4r79pHCzNYP29K39